title: For Sale/Trade:  SIG W. German P220 old style w/ Euro mag release, spur hammer
postcontent: I'm the 3rd owner of this P220, and have put about 150 rounds through it.  I'm a huge fan of SIGs, especially these older models, so it's mostly been a range toy I take care of.  It's kind of a niche SIG, so I'm not in a huge rush to sell it.This is an Interarms imported SIG W. German P220 .45 ACP pistol.  Date code is "JE," which means this is 1986 vintage.  It has all the classic features collectors like me seek:  the original fire control group with the spur hammer and half-cock notch (modern SIGs use a rebound spring and have no half cock notch).  It has the Euro-style magazine release on the heel.  The downside is this means it cannot use modern 8-rd P220 mags with the plastic baseplate.Includes (2) 7-round SIG magazines.   ---  I have (3) other 7-round mags that fit these Euro-release P220s, and also (3) New Old Stock SIG OEM floorplates that can be placed on modern P220 magazines.  Since the floorplate is flat, it converts them to 7-round mags just like the originals.  Any potential buyers are welcome to inquire about working out a deal to include extra magazines and/or floorplates to convert 3 more mags.It has some standard holster wear, as I believe the first owner was a LEO who carried it as a duty gun.  I'm happy to entertain serious inquires from other SIG fanatics like me.  In the coming days I will try to shoot better pictures and would be happy to send any specific angles to any serious SIG enthusiasts who are interested.

postcontent: Selling a 1979 Cadillac Coupe Deville with about 170,000 miles. It was stored in a garage from the late 90s up until the winter of 2014 when I acquired it. It ran beautifully. I redid plugs, plug wires, alternator, transmission gasket and filter. My truck died last winter and I had to drive it a few weeks while I bought a new truck. Because of this there are now a few spots behind the rear fenders of surface rust. Before this the car was spotless. Underneath its still really nice. I also needed a sandbag in the back that winter and because of this I accidentally bottomed out the tail pipe and put a small hole in the exhaust so it's a little louder than it should be. It runs a little rough after its warmed up now and when I took it in, the shop said it had something to do with the thermostat in the carburetor. They suggested a new carburetor would be easier than trying to find that one specific part. I know nothing about carburetors so I can't verify the accuracy of that information. The transmission gasket is leaking pretty good. It shifts beautifully once it's filled with fluid though, no slipping at all. There is a minor coolant system leak and I have to fill the reservoir about every 2 weeks. Some other minor things include the power antenna not working, the headlights wiring is old and the lights are dim. The headliner is sagging. Some of the LED in the original stereo are burnt out and not all of speakers work. This car is all original and still in very great shape. Looking to trade for a quality 1911. I'd like the Sig Emperor Scorpion model ideally + cash to come out to a total of $2000. I have my Minnesota Carry permit.

These are the best tracer bullets for Reloading!
